content:
@WG-prioritization/alerts issue #89712 has been requested for prioritization.

Procedure

  • Priority?
  • Regression?
  • Notify people/groups?
  • Needs I-nominated?
Not a regression as far as I'm aware. Or at least not a recent regression.
I am not sure how priority labels work for rustdoc. This sounds like a P-medium for rustdoc team, but P-low for Rust overall.

This sounds like a P-medium for rustdoc team, but P-low for Rust overall.

I'm not quite sure what the difference between "for rustdoc team" and "for Rust overall" is.
T-rustdoc issues are not really different from T-compiler issues.

My thought is that this is more like a cosmetic issue and isn't a priority to fix for end users (who read the docs), hence P-low. But fixing it could result in some cleanup/improvement of intenral workings of cross-crate reexports in rustdoc, and in that regard it's more P-medium.

But fixing it could result in some cleanup/improvement of intenral workings of cross-crate reexports in rustdoc, and in that regard it's more P-medium.

Not necessarily; cleaning up cross-crate reexports would be much more involved.
But I'm okay with marking this as P-low, especially since it's not a regression (at least, not a recent one).

Gary Guo said:

I am not sure how priority labels work for rustdoc. This sounds like a P-medium for rustdoc team, but P-low for Rust overall.

@Gary Guo this might help for more context on how we wg-prio try to support T-rustdoc
https://rust-lang.zulipchat.com/#narrow/stream/227806-t-compiler.2Fwg-prioritization/topic/Should.20rustdoc.20issues.20be.20triaged.3F/near/245605169

summary is that t-rustdoc issues are "guests" here, t-rustdoc check on them and we wg-prio ensure that (possibly) high priority ones don't get missed
